## Q5. What is the sliding window algorithm and how would you use it to detect anomalies in Informatica's real-time data quality monitoring?

**Why interviewers ask it:** Streaming data quality monitoring requires efficient windowed statistics — a core Informatica Cloud use case.

**What a strong answer looks like:** Explains fixed vs. sliding windows, incremental statistic computation (O(1) update vs. O(n) recompute), Z-score and IQR-based anomaly detection, and stream processing integration.

**Sample answer:** A sliding window of size W maintains a rolling view of the last W data points. Naively recomputing statistics on each slide is O(W); incrementally it's O(1) using **Welford's online algorithm** for running mean and variance: on each new value, update mean and M2 (sum of squared deviations) in one pass — no storage of the full window needed. For Informatica's real-time data quality: **Null rate anomaly** — sliding window count of nulls; alert when the null rate exceeds baseline mean + 3σ (Z-score > 3). **Value distribution shift** — sliding window histogram with chi-squared test vs. baseline distribution; alert on significant divergence. **Volume anomaly** — sliding window record count; alert when count deviates > 2σ from same-hour baseline. Integration: implement as a Flink stateful operator with a tumbling window for baseline statistics (daily) and a sliding window (5-minute slide, 1-hour window) for real-time monitoring. This gives sub-minute detection latency for data quality regressions in production Informatica pipelines.

**Red flags to avoid:**
- Recomputing statistics from scratch on every window slide (O(W) instead of O(1))
- Not distinguishing fixed window from sliding window
- No baseline comparison (just detecting high absolute values, not relative anomalies)

